   <font class="ArticleSource"><big>Editorial:</big></font>

   <font class="ArticleHead"><big>&quot;We are the Jockeys, Jockeys are We&quot;</big></font>

   <font class="ArticleAuthorLight">&nbsp;filed by </font><font class="ArticleAuthor">Kohath</font>

   <div align="right">
   <font class="ArticleTime">01/07/2002 08:36 PM CST</font>
   <div align="left">
   <font class="ArticleText"><big>In the Shadow of the Nerf Bat</big><p>A paladin asks:<p><small><i>I am considering purchasing a horse for a couple of different reasons:<br>1. It looks cool <br>2. You can meditate and engage in combat in outside zones.<br>3. It makes you a little faster than running.<p>If all three of these reasons hold true, I think I will buy one...but if reason number 2, meditating while fighting, is nerfed...I think I would rather wait and just use my AA points to get a Holy Steed.<p>Thus, my question is this. Is meditating and engaging in combat an unforseen consequence of horses that will be nerfed or is it legitimate? This will weigh heavily upon my decision on purchasing a horse so I would appreciate a clarification on this issue.<p>Thanks<p>Ulric Pentalus<br>Cavalier of Marr<br>Saryrn</i></small><p>And Absor responds:<p><small><b>Horses were not intended to a character to meditate while fighting. That is indeed something we will be fixing in the very near future.<p>Alan</b></small><p>Now I don't play a hybrid, and I can't afford a horse.  But the ability to meditate while fighting on your horse is, by far the <b>number one, most beneficial feature</b> of owning a mount.  If this benefit is removed, a large number of hybrids are going to want their money--or their skill points--back.<p><big>Backing Away From the Brink</big><p>This nerf happened in today's patch.  I doubt very much that any appeal to Verant will change that.  And lets face it, it probably <i>should</i> have been nerfed.  Horses were supposed to be for travel, not for mana conservation.<p>Look at it this way. Say you go up to a vending machine and decide to buy a Baby Ruth bar in slot C10. You put in your sixty cents and make your selection, and two candy bars drop down. The next day you go to the vending machine again, put in your money and pick C10, and once again you get two candy bars. Let's say this goes on for a whole month, with you getting a free candy bar every day. Then, one day, you stop getting the free candy. You can hardly call the vending machine owner and complain that you should keep getting a free candy bar; it was clearly a mistake that you ever got one in the first place. You should just be happy that you got something for free, at least for a while.<p>But how does Verant nerf without undue consequences to innocent equestrians?  Easy: <b>remove the NO DROP from the horse bridles</b>.  If you feel cheated, sell your horse to another player.  Someone will certainly buy it.<p>Verant could also allow horses to be sold back to the stable master for 90% (or more) of the purchase price.<p><big>A Little Horse Sense</big><p>Now let's take a step back from the rider's empty purse and the horse's coat, still glossy with empty promise.  We need some room to get a little perspective on the situation.  There's a bigger picture here.<p>The largest part of this controversy was caused by Verant's policy of deliberate secrecy.  Verant is rarely forthcoming with information.  What's working as intended?  What's broken?  Verant doesn't generally enlighten us.  They keep it a secret.<p>Why?  Because you're supposed to learn things for yourself in EverQuest.  You're supposed to explore and marvel at what you see and you're supposed to wonder exactly how the world works.  Then when your quest for knowledge is complete, when you finally reach the end of the long road, you'll feel the joy of genuine accomplishment.  That's by design, and it's a good idea.<p>But Verant takes it way, way too far.  Bugs go un-acknowledged and un-fixed because there's no way to <i>prove</i> something isn't working as intended without knowing the intentions.  GM quests are misunderstood, resented, and finally stopped altogether because no one ever really understands the story.  Innocents are banned for exploiting bugs of which they are ignorant.  And the general relationship between Verant and the players can never be an entirely trusting one because Verant refuses to be forthcoming.<p>Verant needs to begin opening up a little more.  Start telling us some things about the world.  Not everything is a &quot;spoiler&quot;; some things are just information.  Tell us what we need to know.  Remember how long it took to find out what exactly stats do?<p><big>The System Failed</big><p>This time, the players did what they were supposed to.  Players went out and purchased horses.  Through observation and experience, they learned the benefits of the equestrian lifestyle.  All the ups and downs of horse ownership were learned without Verant spoiling a single thing.  <p>The players who could afford it used this knowledge and bought more horses.  Now they're being told their observations were improper--not incorrect, just improper.  And with this nerf, it's their loss.  The system failed.  Change the system.</font>
  </td>
 </tr>
